---
title: Sweet Soy Chicken Two Ways Keep It Simple with Lo Mein + Mix It Up: Spicy Szechuan Rice Bowl
description: Do you like cooking two different meals every night? Of course not! So here’s our 2-in-1 solution: You’ll stir-fry juicy chicken with tender edamame in our sweet soy glaze, then toss half of it with chewy lo mein noodles Combine the rest of the chicken in the pan with red cabbage and spicy Szechuan sauce, then serve it over fluffy rice with as much Sriracha as you like for those that like a bit of spice. And kaboom! One meal, two ways, all at the same time.
This recipe is designed to make Sweet Soy Chicken two ways. Nutrition for the Keep it Simple version with Lo Mein is as follows: Calories: 940, Fat: 15 g, Saturated Fat: 3 g, Cholesterol: 35 mg, Sodium: 2420 mg, Total Carbs: 144 g, Fiber: 11g, Sugar: 33 g, Protein: 54 g. Nutrition for the Mix it Up version with Spicy Szechuan Sauce & Rice is as follows: Calories: 1030, Fat: 28 g, Saturated Fat: 10 g, Cholesterol: 165 mg, Sodium: 3440 mg, Total Carbs: 142 g, Fiber: 8 g, Sugar: 38 g, Protein: 47 g. Nutrition for both versions is representative of a 1/2 meal serving.
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/65f08348f15f35246a8cb18a-65543e36.jpeg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipecards/card/65f08348f15f35246a8cb18a.pdf
servings: 2
course: main course
cuisine: East Asia
author: Sara Heilman
time required: 30 minutes
source: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipes/sweet-soy-chicken-two-ways-65f08348f15f35246a8cb18a
---

Bring a #medium pot{} of @salt{}ed water to a boil. Wash and dry produce.

In a #small pot{}, combine @Jasmine Rice{1/2%cup}, @water{3/4%cup} (1 1/2 cups
for 4 servings), and a @salt{pinch}. Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce
heat to low. Cook until rice is tender, ~{15-18%minutes}. Keep covered off heat
until ready to serve.

While rice cooks, core, deseed, and dice @Bell Pepper{1}(cored and diced into
1/2-inch pieces). Halve, peel, and dice @Shallot{1}(halved, peeled, and diced
into 1/2-inch pieces). Peel and mince @Ginger{1%thumb}(peeled and minced).

Once medium pot of water is boiling, add @Lo Mein Noodles{4.5%ounce}. Cook,
stirring occasionally, until al dente, ~{5-7%minutes}. Turn off heat. Drain
and thoroughly rinse under cold water, then return to pot.

While noodles cook, in a #medium bowl{}, combine @Sweet Soy Glaze{1/2%cup},
@Cornstarch{1%tablespoon}, and @water{1%cup} (1 1/2 cups for 4 servings). Whisk
until cornstarch has dissolved; set aside.

Open package of @Diced Chicken Thighs{10%ounce} and drain off any excess liquid.

Heat a large drizzle of @Cooking Oil{2%teaspoon} in a #large pan{} over
medium-high heat. Add bell pepper, shallot, and ginger; season with @Salt{}
and @Pepper{}.

Cook, stirring occasionally, until veggies begin to soften, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Add chicken and @Edamame{4%ounce} to pan with veggies; stir to combine (add
another drizzle of oil if pan seems dry). Cook, stirring occasionally, until
chicken is browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Add sweet soy mixture; stir to evenly coat. Cook until sauce has thickened
slightly, ~{30-60%seconds} (1-2 minutes for 4 servings). Remove pan from heat.

Transfer half the chicken and veggies to #pot{} with drained noodles. Toss to
combine. Season with salt to taste. Cover to keep warm.

Return pan with remaining chicken and veggies to medium heat. Add
@Shredded Red Cabbage{4%ounce} and @Szechuan Paste{2%tablespoon}; stir to combine.

Cook, stirring, until stir-fry is fragrant and cabbage softens slightly,
~{1-2%minutes}.

== Keep It Simple ==

Divide chicken lo mein between #bowls{} and serve.

== Mix It Up ==

Fluff rice with a #fork{}; stir in @Butter{1%tablespoon} (2 TBSP for 4 servings).
Divide rice between bowls and top with spicy chicken stir-fry. Drizzle with
@Sriracha{1%teaspoon} to taste and serve.

> Chicken is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 165°.